trends.name: Court Sneakers
trends.description:
• Inspired by retro tennis sneakers
  • Usually constructed with lace-up closures, though velcro can also be found.
  • Two facing quarters form the upper, starting at the sole, while the tongue extends seamlessly into the toe box.
  • Mostly low-top, but can be high-top
  • Usually designed with a flat, low-profile sole made of rubber.
  • The upper is generally made from leather or suede, with a clean silhouette.


Not to confuse with:

  • Canvas Trainers: Similar in shape, but in canvas with a rubber toe-cap.
  • Plimsolls: Always have a vamp insert until the throat line. Mostly in canvas or jersey upper.
  • Retro Football Sneakers: Wider shape, without two facing quarters, generally have a suede toe-cap.
  • Retro Basketball Sneakers: Chunkier design. The toe part has a perforated overlay piece of leather covering the frontal and side parts of the toe box.

positive_images.description: Two laced side parts, tongue goes seamlessly to the round-shaped toes
Minimal design, flat rubber sole
Must have a leather upper
Can be high-top, always in leather

trends.name: Performance Running Sneakers
trends.description:
• Technical and profiled sneakers, usually made from lightweight, breathable mesh or engineered knit
  • Slight to pronounced cushioning system, with slightly elevated heel-to-toe drop
  • The sole may show a gap between the toes and heel


Not to be confused with:

  • Lifestyle Running Sneakers: Chunkier midsoles for style rather than propulsion. Leather, suede, or fashion-driven uppers (less breathable, less flexible).
  • Retro Running Sneakers: Inspired by vintage performance models, not showing advanced technology, built for casual wear. Uppers in less performance-oriented materials.
  • Retro Trainers: Heavier design and soles, also known as "Dad Sneakers", often showing a visible separation between heel and forefoot. Complex uppers with elaborated material mixes.
  • Trail Sneakers: More robust design, with bulkier outsoles with visible lugs. Often paired with a hiking lacing system.

positive_images.description: Breathable technical knit and/or mesh uppers
Gap between the toes and the heel
Elevated heel-to-toe drop
Thick but light foam soles

trends.name: Retro Running Sneakers
trends.description:
• Inspired by 1970s running shoes
  • They have an almond-shaped toecap
  • Layered uppers are made from leather, suede, or mixed materials
  • There is a distinct overlays on the toe box and heel counter
  • They have a low-profile sole sloping from thin heel to ultra-thin toe
  • Lace-up closure


Not to be confused with:

  • Lifestyle Running Sneakers: Chunkier midsoles, more technical uppers
  • Retro Football Sneakers: Flat sole, no slope at the front
  • Retro Trainers: Heavier build, thick soles, complex mixed-material uppers
  • Retro Basketball Sneakers: Flat soles, flat toe cap, leather uppers with perforations

positive_images.description: Low-profile sole, which often slopes subtly from a thin heel to an even thinner toe.
Lace-up closure.
They feature an almond-shaped toecap.
Made from leather, suede, or a mix of materials, with distinct overlays on the toe box and heel counter.

trends.name: Lifestyle Running Sneakers
trends.description:
• Streamlined design, but with more emphasis on aesthetics and casual comfort (all-day wear) than performance efficiency
  • Heavier and less breathable than performance uppers. May include overlays, logos, or decorative stitching
  • Midsoles are often very creative, chunkier, and designed as a style element (e.g., visible air units)


Not to confuse with:

  • Performance Running Sneakers: Much lighter and minimalistic. Breathable mesh uppers and visible performance tech. Thick foam outsole with more traction and flex grooves.
  • Retro Running Sneakers: Inspired by vintage performance models, not showing advanced technology, built for casual wear. Uppers in less performance-oriented materials.
  • Retro Trainers: Heavier design and soles. Also known as "Dad Sneakers." Retro-tech inspiration. Often shows a visible separation between the heel and forefoot. Complex uppers with elaborated material mixes.
  • Trail Sneakers: Outdoor running designs, with bulky outsoles showing visible lugs. Often paired with a hiking lacing system.

positive_images.description: Creative midsoles with air inserts
Urban styles and details
City wear design rather than performance-oriented
Inspired by running, but worn with casual looks

trends.name: Performance Football Sneakers
trends.description:
• Made to play professional Football
  • They have a slim, profiled shape
  • The uppers in knit or leather, with textured effects and padded topstitching
  • Large visible crampons or lug soles, in varied designs
  • Lace-up closure, sometimes with integrated ankle-sock knit
  • Bold logos, graphic lines, and color-blocking


Not to be confused with:

  • Boxing Sneakers: Higher, rigid ankle not suited for flexibility
  • Retro Football Sneakers: Suede uppers with no visible crampons

positive_images.description: Bright and colorful designs with visible cleats (crampons).
Performance material with ankle socks.
Tight fit
Thin profile

trends.name: Retro Football Sneakers
trends.description:
• They are made from leather and suede only, no technical materials
  • They have a topstitched upper for a lightly padded look
  • They often feature a contrasting toe cap and sometimes an extra-long tongue
  • They have a straight, thin rubber sole, usually in brown, black, or off-white


Not to be confused with:

  • Performance Football Sneakers: Technical materials, ankle socks, and visible cleats
  • Skater Sneakers: Thicker soles, wide laces
  • Plimsolls: Vamp insert extends up to the throat line
  • Slip-On Sneakers: No visible closure, thicker rubber sole

positive_images.description: Tone on tone or contrasting suede or leather toe-cap
Extra-long tongue
Inspired by vintage terrace sneakers
Contrasting rubber soles from the upper colors.

trends.name: Performance Basketball Sneakers
trends.description:
• They feature leather or technical uppers such as mesh or nylon, designed for breathability, support, and durability while playing basketball
  • They come in high or low top styles; high tops typically have tongues that rise higher than the back collar
  • They often feature a top line with a deep curve, especially on high-cut designs for better ankle mobility
  • They are designed with lace-up closures, often reinforced for a secure fit during gameplay
  • They feature layered, textured, or bubble-like soles engineered to provide traction, cushioning, and stability on indoor courts


Not to be confused with:

  • Performance Running Shoes: Inclined soles with minimal ankle support
  • Canvas Sneakers: Canvas uppers paired with flat rubber soles
  • Retro Basketball Sneakers: Leather uppers with design references to court shoes, but lacking modern performance features
  • Performance Football Sneakers: Visible cleats and sock-like collar details designed for turf or grass surfaces

positive_images.description: Deep curve on the top line.
Textured soles with performance materials on the upper.
High top basketball sneakers with higher tongue compared to the back height.
High tops with sleek design to offer ankle support during playing.

trends.name: Retro Basketball Sneakers
trends.description:
• Features uppers in leather or rubber, often with perforations on the toe box
  • Designed with a lace-up closure, sometimes including extra eyelets at the collar (on high tops)
  • Available in high or low top styles; high tops typically have a higher front collar than back
  • They have a leather overlay on the toe, wrapping around the front and sides of the toe box


Not to be confused with:

  • Performance Basketball Sneakers: Deep sole curves, more technical construction
  • Retro Football Sneakers: Suede uppers with flat, contrasting soles
  • Canvas Sneakers: Canvas uppers with rubber soles
  • Boxing Sneakers: Higher overall cut with tighter ankle fit

positive_images.description: Perforation details on the upper part of the shoes.
High top sneakers with the front part being higher than the back.
There is a separate piece with two eyelets for closure.
Leather, non-performance, upper materials with reference to performance basketball shoes, therefore these are Retro Basketball Sneakers.

trends.name: Retro Trainers
trends.description:
• Chunky, sculpted sole with carved lines and often a bridge between heel and forefoot
  • Layered uppers made from mesh, leather, suede, rubber, and plastic
  • Feature cut-outs, inserts, and graphic overlays in tone-on-tone or contrasting finishes
  • Design emphasizes a structured, rigid build with a retro yet technical look


Not to be confused with:

  • Lifestyle Running Sneakers: Leather/suede uppers, less breathable
  • Retro Running Sneakers: Simpler silhouette, casual use, non-technical materials
  • Trail Sneakers: Bulkier outsoles with lugs, often with hiking-style lacing
  • Performance Running Sneakers: Lightweight, breathable mesh, visible tech, flexible foam soles

positive_images.description: They feature a the thick, sculpted sole with sinuous, carved lines and often a bridge element connecting the heel and forefoot.
The upper is made from a mix of materials, including mesh, leather or suede, plastic, and rubber.
They have complex inserts, cut-outs, and multilayered panels.
"Dad sneakers," inspired by the '80s and '90s aesthetic.

trends.name: Plimsoll Sneakers
trends.description:
• They feature a low-cut profile that sits below the ankle, with a slim, lightweight upper made from canvas or similar textile materials
  • They are commonly designed with a simple eyelet-and-lace closure, offering secure fastening without additional structure or padding
  • They feature a thin, flat vulcanized rubber sole that offers basic grip and durability, with a distinct separation between the upper and sole
  • They always feature a vamp insert that extends all the way to the throat line, giving them their classic, minimal silhouette


Not to be confused with:

  • Skater Shoes: Heavier and more cushioned, often with reinforced toe caps, padded collars, and thicker rubber outsoles
  • Court Sneakers: Similar shape, but made out of leather or suede. Lacks the continuous vamp insert that reaches the throat line.
  • Canvas Sneakers: Similar in material but lack the continuous vamp insert that reaches the throat line
  • Retro Football Sneakers: Typically have suede uppers and flat, contrasting rubber soles, designed with sport styling

positive_images.description: They feature a flat rubber sole
Made from canvas or similar textile materials
Simple eyelet-and-lace closure
They always feature a vamp insert that extends all the way to the throat line

trends.name: Skater Sneakers
trends.description:
• They feature flat, straight soles designed to maximize contact with the skateboard deck for grip and control
  • They feature slim uppers made from durable materials like canvas or suede, offering flexibility and board feel
  • They are designed with lace-up closures, usually with wide laces and padded tongues for comfort and easy adjustment
  • They feature low-cut padded collars to protect the ankle area during impact or tricks
  • They are built for skateboarding but commonly worn casually due to their simple, functional design


Not to be confused with:

  • Retro Basketball Sneakers: Heavier leather builds with thicker soles
  • Slip-On Sneakers: No laces, minimal support, and not suited for skateboarding
  • Retro Football Sneakers: Suede uppers with slim soles
  • Court Sneakers: Fully made out of leather with no padded tongues

positive_images.description: They typically feature a straight, flat sole to provide optimal contact with the skateboard deck.
Lace-up closures are generally loose, with wide or oversized laces, often threaded through chunky, padded tongues.
Originally designed for skateboarding.
The uppers are made from flexible, breathable materials like canvas or suede.

trends.name: Canvas Trainers
trends.description:
• They feature uppers made from canvas fabric, often with suede or leather reinforcements for added durability and style
  • They have a flat rubber soles, though some models have chunky or irregular sole designs
  • They feature lace-up closures, but slip-on versions and alternatives like zippers or elastic gores also exist
  • They feature two facing quarters that rise from the sole and connect to a canvas tongue, forming the upper structure, including the vamp and toe box
  • They were originally designed as performance basketball shoes, now worn casually for their versatility and breathable materials


Not to be confused with:

  • Plimsoll Sneakers: Feature canvas uppers but always include a vamp insert extending to the throat line and a more minimal, uniform construction
  • Court Sneakers: Similar shape, but made out of leather or suede.
  • Skater Sneakers: Heavier, with padded collars, suede uppers, and flat soles built specifically for skateboarding
  • Retro Football Sneakers: Suede uppers and flat, contrasting soles.

positive_images.description: They feature uppers made from canvas fabric
They feature lace-up closures, but slip-on versions and alternatives also exist
They feature two facing quarters that rise from the sole and connect to a canvas tongue
They have a flat rubber soles, though some models have chunky or irregular sole designs

trends.name: Slip-On Sneakers
trends.description:
• They feature no laces or fasteners, instead using elastic side gores or stretch panels for easy on-off and a secure fit
  • They are built with flat rubber soles, often vulcanized, offering durability, grip, and lightweight flexibility
  • They feature a one-piece vamp that extends across the top of the foot and connects directly to the quarters, with no separate tongue
  • They are always low-top and can be made from various materials, including canvas, leather, or synthetics


Not to be confused with:

  • Plimsoll Sneakers: Feature lace-up closures and a distinct vamp insert reaching the throat line
  • Sock Sneakers: Built from stretch-knit materials with a high-top, sock-like collar and sculpted midsoles.
  • Moccasins: Typically made from soft leather with stitched uppers and little to no sole structure. Also, no stretch side panels.
  • Clogs: Backless or semi-backless shoes, often with rigid uppers and thick, molded soles. Generally wider than a sneaker.

positive_images.description: They are built with flat rubber soles
No laces or fasteners, instead using elastic side gores
Made from various materials, including canvas, leather, or synthetics
They feature a one-piece vamp that extends across the top of the foot

trends.name: Sock Sneakers
trends.description:
• They feature a laceless, pull-on construction that mimics the shape and fit of a high sock, made from stretch-knit materials
  • They are built on lightweight rubber soles, often chunky or sculpted, providing cushioning and flexibility
  • They feature seamless knit uppers that extend from the sole to the ankle (or higher), offering breathability and a snug, glove-like fit
  • They are designed with minimal external panels, relying on knit tension and the sole structure to maintain shape and support


Not to be confused with:

  • Lifestyle Running Sneakers: May use knit uppers, but include laces, structured overlays, and performance-inspired design cues
  • Performance Running Sneakers: Designed for athletic use with a technical design, reinforced uppers, arch support, and performance soles
  • Sock Boots: Share a sock-like fit but often have heel construction, and boot shape
  • Slip-On Sneakers: Low-cut with elastic gores but without the extended knit collar or sculpted soles

trends.name: Jeans
trends.description:
"Jeans" are a specific style of denim pants that include classic design elements like five pockets, rivets, a fly, and back yoke stitching. They can come in any color and a variety of fits, including "Skinny", "Flared", "Wide-Leg", "Straight", or "Bootcut".
While all "Jeans" are made from denim, not all "Denim Pants" are "Jeans": "Jeans" must have the traditional construction details that define the style.
"Denim Pants" without these characteristic features (e.g., lacking pockets or having a trouser-style cut) are not considered "Jeans", even if made from denim fabric.

children.name: Mom Jeans

trends.name: Fit and Flare Pants
trends.description:
"Fit and Flare Pants" is the parent trend that includes both "Bootcut Pants" and "Bell Bottom Pants" as child trends. It refers to all pants, regardless of fabric, that are fitted through the thigh and flare out from the knee. The degree of flare varies: slight for "Bootcut", dramatic for "Bell-Bottoms". These fits differ from "Flared Pants" (which flare subtly from the crotch) and "Wide-Leg Pants" (which flare dramatically from the crotch).
The mood board will include all "Bootcut" and "Bell Bottom" pants, in any fabric, closure, or styling, as long as the silhouette follows these shapes.

children.name: Bootcut Pants
children.description:
"Bootcut Pants" (and "Bell Bottom Pants") are child trends of the "Fit & Flare" parent trend. Bootcut Pants include all styles with this specific fit, regardless of fabric. The "Bootcut" silhouette is fitted through the thighs and flares out slightly from the knee (originally designed to slip over a pair of boots). The flare is more subtle than that of "Bell Bottoms". This fit is also referred to as "Jazz" when describing leggings, or "Kick Flare" in some variations.
"Bootcut Pants" can be cropped or full-length. The mood board will include all materials, closures, and styles, as long as the silhouette matches this shape.

children.name: Bell Bottom Pants
children.description:
"Bell Bottom Pants" (and "Bootcut Pants") are the child trends of the "Fit & Flare" parent trend. Bell Bottom fits closely through the thighs and flares out dramatically from the knee. The flare is more exaggerated than that of “Bootcut”.
The mood board will include all materials, closures, and styles, as long as the silhouette matches this shape.

trends.name: Flared Pants
trends.description:
"Flared Pants" refers to all pants, regardless of fabric, that flare subtly from the crotch. This fit differs from "Wide-Leg Pants" (which flare dramatically from the crotch), "Fit & Flare" (the parent trend of "Bootcut" and "Bell Bottoms"), which includes the pants that are fitted through the thigh and flare out from the knee. The degree of flare varies: slight for "Bootcut", dramatic for "Bell-Bottoms"
The mood board will include all "Flared Pants", in any fabric, closure, or styling, as long as the silhouette follows this shape

trends.name: Wide-Leg Pants

"Wide-Leg Pants" refers to all pants, regardless of fabric, that flare dramatically from the crotch. This fit differs from "Flared Pants" (which flare subtly from the crotch), "Fit & Flare" (the parent trend of "Bootcut" and "Bell Bottoms") which includes the pants that are fitted through the thigh and flare out from the knee, and "Baggy Pants", that are oversized pants with a low crotch and waist.
The mood board will include all "Wide-Leg Pants", in any fabric, closure, or styling, as long as the silhouette follows this shape

trends.name: Checked
trends.description:
• Checked print is formed by intersecting horizontal and vertical lines that create repeated squares or rectangles.
  • This is a parent category that encompasses the prints Gingham, Plaid, Prince of Wales, Windowpane, Checkerboard, Lumberjack, and Argyle.
  • It can be used on any garment, in any fabric, and any color, making it one of the most versatile design motifs in fashion.
  • To be considered a checked print, a pattern must feature a grid-based structure. Designs that don’t follow this format are not classified as checks.

children.name: Tiger Print
children.description:
• Pattern: Irregular, curved horizontal or diagonal stripes inspired by tiger skin
  • Colors: Typically black or dark brown stripes over an orange or golden base (sometimes beige, tan, or stylized in fashion as neon or pastel)
  • By contrast, even if it looks similar, Zebra Print is typically limited to black and white.
  • We don't consider figurative animal prints in this trend

children.name: Zebra
children.description:
• Pattern: Clean black-and-white stripes with sharp contrast inspired by zebra skin
  • Not to be confused with Tiger Print, which is typically black or dark brown stripes over an orange or golden base (sometimes beige, tan, or stylized in fashion as neon or pastel)
  • We don't consider figurative animal prints in this trend
